        optionFeedback: [`RAS proteins are not targeted by E7 or the other important HPV oncoprotein, E6, a protein that inhibits the function of the p53 tumor suppressor. `,`Laminin is a basement membrane protein; it is not a target of E6 or E7. `,`High risk HPV infection has no direct effect on DNA repair proteins. By inhibiting p53 via the viral E6 oncoprotein, however, it can indirectly cause genomic instability by impairing DNA repair. This second indirect effect of high-risk HPV infection (inhibition of p53) is an important contributor to the virus’ ability to cause cancer. `,`The viral E7 proteins encoded by high-risk HPVs such as HPV-16 bind and inhibit RB, a critical regulator of the G1/S cell cycle checkpoint, thereby preventing cell cycle arrest. This has two oncogenic effects: (1) it increases cellular proliferation; and (2) by preventing cell cycle arrest, which is a normal part of DNA repair, it accelerates the acquisition of genomic aberrations that may lead to activation of oncogenes and inactivation of tumor suppressor genes.  `,`Epidermal growth factor receptor is not a target of the oncoproteins of high-risk HPV.`],
