        q: `A girl is born with a single functional copy of a tumor suppressor gene. At the age of 1 year, the remaining normal allele is lost through mutation, resulting in the development of a tumor from a cell that has lost both copies of the gene. Cell cycle analysis of tumor cells shows that control of transition from G1 to the S phase is lost. Which of the following neoplasms is most likely to arise via this mechanism?`,
        q2: ``,
        q3: [],
        option: [`Retinoblastoma`, ` Breast carcinoma`,`Adenocarcinoma of colon`,`Ovarian carcinoma`,`Chronic myeloid leukemia`],
        optionFeedback: [`In its hereditary from, retinoblastoma stems from inheritance of one defective copy of the RB gene, which encodes the retinoblastoma protein, RB. RB integrates pro-growth and anti-growth signals to control progression from the G1 to the S phases of the cell cycle, beyond which cells proceed through mitosis and divide. RB is active in its hypophosphorylated state, a form that inhibits the expression of genes needed for DNA synthesis. Pro-growth signals phosphorylate and inhibit RB, allowing cells to move from the G1 phase into S phase. In patients with one defective copy of the RB gene, sporadic mutations almost inevitably lead to complete loss of RB function in at least a few retinoblasts, rapidly proliferating cells that are found in the developing retina. This leads to unbridled proliferation and (with acquisition of additional mutations), retinoblastoma, an aggressive tumor, usually in both eyes.  `,`Familial breast cancer is most commonly associated with inherited mutations in tumor suppressor genes that are important in maintaining genomic stability (BRCA1, BRCA2, TP53). `,`Familial colon cancer is most commonly associated with mutations in tumor suppressor genes that are required for DNA mismatch repair (Lynch Syndrome) or in the tumor suppressor gene APC, which encodes a negative regulator of the Wnt signaling pathway. `,`Familial ovarian cancer is most commonly associated with inherited mutations in tumor suppressor genes that are important in maintaining genomic stability (BRCA1, BRCA2, TP53). `,`Chronic myeloid leukemia (CML) is associated with a gain of function BCR-ABL fusion gene, which encodes a constitutively active tyrosine kinase. CML is not an inherited form of cancer.`],
