        q: `A 60-year-old man presents with increasing fatigue. Physical examination is unremarkable. Laboratory investigations show he is anemic. Stool examination is positive for occult blood. Radiologic investigation revealed an irregular mass in the descending colon. During colonoscopy, a biopsy was performed, illustrated here. Which of the following molecular abnormalities in this lesion is most likely to render the cells resistant to chemotherapy-induced death?`,
        q2: `<img src="../images/f005-q004-9780323640251.png"/>`,
        q3: [],
        option: [` Mutational inactivation of the RB gene`, `Amplification of the RAS gene`,` Mutational inactivation of the TP53 gene`,` Overexpression of the APC gene`,` Loss of heterozygosity of the NF-1 gene`],
        optionFeedback: [`Mutational inactivation of RB may increase proliferation, which in some instances might increase sensitivity to chemotherapy. `,`RAS is activated by point mutations, not by amplification. RAS is not directly involved in cell death pathways triggered by chemotherapeutic agents. `,` One of the ways that many forms of chemotherapy kill cells is by inducing DNA damage, which leads to activation of the p53 protein. p53 causes cell cycle arrest, providing time for DNA repair, and if the damage is too severe, activates members of the BCL2 family that trigger apoptosis via the intrinsic (mitochondrial) pathway. If p53 function is lost (by mutation of TP53 or overexpression of p53 inhibitors such as MDM2), this response fails and cells may survive damage that would otherwise kill them. Moreover, DNA damage goes unrepaired, leading to genomic instability and rapid accumulation of a high burden of mutations. It is increasingly apparent that loss of p53 function is a common cause of resistance to chemotherapy in a broad spectrum of cancers.  `,`APC is a tumor suppressor and is lost in cancer; it is not overexpressed. `,`NF1 protein is a negative regulator of RAS and its loss promotes growth.`],
