        optionFeedback: [`t( 9:22) is characteristic of chronic myeloid leukemia. This translocation causes the formation of a BCR-ABL fusion gene whose protein product has constitutive tyrosine kinase activity, which in turn causes uncontrolled cell proliferation. Several inhibitors of BCR-ABL are highly effective in treating chronic myeloid leukemia.  `,`All-trans retinoic acid (ATRA) is a highly specific targeted treatment for acute promyelocytic leukemia, which is caused by a t(15;17) that fuses part of the PML gene to the retinoic acid receptor alpha (RARA) gene. The fusion protein blocks maturation of hematopoietic progenitor cells and thus allows immature cells to proliferate unchecked. ATRA binds to the PML-RARA protein and inhibits its function, in part by triggering its proteolytic degradation. This removes the differentiation blockade and induces the terminal differentiation of leukemia cells into neutrophils, which have short lifespans and rapidly die, resulting in clearance of the leukemia from the marrow and the blood. `,`HER2 inhibitors are used in cancers that have amplification of the HER2 gene, which encodes a receptor tyrosine kinase that is a member of the EGF receptor family. HER2 amplification is seen in carcinomas, particularly a subset of breast cancers. `,`Anti-retroviral agents are not used to treat human cancers; they can help to prevent cancer in those with HIV infection by controlling the virus and thus restoring host immunity. `,`Anti-hepatitis C drugs help to prevent hepatocellular carcinoma by curing the infection, which otherwise may become chronic, leading to liver damage, cirrhosis, and sometimes hepatocellular carcinoma.`],
