        optionFeedback: [`Parathyroid hormone (PTH)-related protein increases bone resorption by binding to receptors on osteoblasts, creating signals that stimulate the release of RANKL, a factor that activates osteoclasts. High levels of parathyroid hormone (PTH)-related protein lead to hypercalcemia. This form of paraneoplastic syndrome is associated with non–small cell lung cancer, particularly squamous cell carcinoma of the lung. `,`Erythropoietin drives red cell production from the bone marrow. It is sometimes produced by renal cell carcinoma, hepatocellular carcinoma, and several other tumors. `,`    Hypertension, “moon” facies, and edema are all signs of elevated cortisol levels. ACTH increases expression of corticosteroids such as cortisol from the adrenal cortex. Small cell carcinoma shows neuroendocrine differentiation and often expresses hormones that are not typically released by pulmonary epithelial cells, such as ACTH.    This is a classic example of a paraneoplastic syndrome.  `,`Insulin overproduction leads to hypoglycemia and is most often seen in insulin-producing islet cell tumors. Hypoglycemia may be seen as a paraneoplastic syndrome in fibrosarcomas, other mesenchymal tumors and ovarian carcinomas due to elaboration of insulin and insulin-like substance. `,`Angiotensin is the final product in a hormone “cascade” involving renin, a renal hormone produced in response to renal “underperfusion.” Angiotensin overproduction has been described as a rare cause of paraneoplastic hypertension, most commonly associated with hepatocellular carcinoma.`],
