        optionFeedback: [`Local invasion of chest wall muscle can occur late in the course after spread to the pleura but is unlikely at presentation. Local invasion is not considered metastatic disease but as a sign of local aggression. `,`Rib involvement would be an example of hematogenous spread, which also can occur later in the course. Cancers most likely to spread to bone include breast, lung, thyroid, kidney, and prostate carcinomas. `,`   Carcinomas usually spread via the lymphatics and, therefore, the initial metastasis of a lung cancer is the hilar lymph nodes, a major drainage site of pulmonary lymphatics.  `,`Liver metastases are associated with hematogenous spread and are most common in the setting of colon carcinoma due to tumor cells entering the portal circulation. `,`The brain can be a site of hematogenous spread with many aggressive cancers, including carcinomas, melanomas, and germ cell tumors. In those with lung cancer, brain metastases tend to occur later in the course of the disease.`],
