        optionFeedback: [`Severe dysplasia (often referred to as high risk squamous intraepithelial lesion [HSIL]) caused by high-risk human papillomavirus infection is an important precursor lesion to cervical carcinoma. Furthermore, an early cervical carcinoma may also be present. Therefore, clinical follow up with repeat examination and biopsy and, if necessary surgery, are recommended.  `,`There is no association between ovarian teratoma and high risk squamous intraepithelial lesion, as teratomas are not related to human papillomavirus infection. `,`Once established, cervical carcinoma (unlike squamous intraepithelial lesions) does not regress. The presence of high risk squamous intraepithelial lesions, by contrast, raises the possibility that an early cervical carcinoma might be present and is an indication for surgical removal (conization). `,`Human papillomavirus cannot be treated with antibiotics. It can be prevented in most cases, however, by current vaccines. `,`Human papillomavirus is a classic infectious cause of cancer; risk is not inherited and therefore is not shared by family members.`],
