        optionFeedback: [`Inherited mutations in growth factor receptor genes are associated with a variety of disorders, many non-neoplastic (i.e., achondroplastic dwarfism), but are not associated with colon cancer. `,`Inherited defects in E-cadherin are associated with gastric and breast cancer, but not colon cancer. `,`  A family history of right-sided colon cancer and the finding of scattered polyps elsewhere in the colon are consistent with a diagnosis of hereditary nonpolyposis colon cancer. Affected individuals often present with cancer at early ages that may arise from sessile serrated polyps; however, the polyps are not nearly as numerous as in the other major inherited disorder associated with colon cancer, familial adenomatous polyposis coli, which is caused by mutations in the APC tumor suppressor gene.  `,`Inherited gain of function mutations in cyclin dependent kinase 4 (CDK4) and loss of function mutations in its antagonist, p16 (encoded by the CDKN2A gene) are associated with familial forms of melanoma, but not colon cancer. `,`Loss of pro-apoptotic (Bax, Bak) and activation of anti-apoptotic factors (e.g., Bcl2) are not associated with familial forms of cancer. Overexpression of BCL2, as in follicular lymphomas, protects tumor cells from apoptosis and thus favors survival of cancer cells.`],
