        optionFeedback: [`This is a very common site of metastasis from gastrointestinal tract whose venous drainage is via the portal vein, which supplies the liver. Thus, liver metastases are common in patients with colonic adenocarcinoma and pancreatic adenocarcinoma. `,`Most sarcomas do not commonly spread through lymphatic channels. Inguinal lymph nodes, by contrast, would be a common site for metastasis from a melanoma involving the lower limbs. `,`    Osteosarcoma, as is true of sarcomas generally, has a propensity to spread through blood vessels. The first capillary bed that metastasizing cells in the blood reach from the lower limbs is the lungs.  `,`The brain might be a site of secondary metastasis from lung but would be a very uncommon site for initial metastasis. An exception might be a patient with a patent foramen ovale. Tumors that commonly metastasize to the brain early in their course include lung carcinoma and certain forms of germ cell tumors. `,`This is an unusual site of metastasis except for squamous cell carcinoma of the lung, which seems to have a “tropism” for the adrenal gland. `],
