        optionFeedback: [`Adenocarcinomas are composed of malignant glands of epithelial origin; they lack the other tissue types seen in this specimen. `,`Fibroadenomas contain both benign glands and benign spindled cells resembling fibroblasts but would not contain the other elements seen in this tumor. `,`Hamartoma (frequently a misnomer, because these are usually clonal neoplasms) is composed of a benign neoplastic stromal component and reactive epithelial cells, often gland-forming. It also does not contain some of the elements seen in this neoplasm (e.g., hair, several types of epithelium). `,`Mesothelioma is composed only of the lining cells of the peritoneum or other serosal surfaces.`,`The presence of tissues from multiple germ layers and of multiple types is diagnostic of teratoma, a type of germ cell tumor. The features in this case are classic for a mature cystic teratoma, also known as a dermoid cyst.  `],
